1. Security & Compliance in Pipelines
    - Security and compliance in CI/CD pipelines ensure your code, dependencies, and deployment processes are safe, auditable, and enforce company policies. This reduces risk of breaches, vulnerabilities, or accidental deployment of bad code.

2. Secrets Management
    - Definition: Protect sensitive information like API keys, database passwords, or tokens used in your pipeline. Never hardcode these in your repo.
    - Tools:
        GitHub Secrets – encrypted secrets in GitHub repos
        HashiCorp Vault – centralized secret management
        AWS Secrets Manager – cloud-based secrets storage
    - Node.js example in GitHub Actions:
        name: Node.js CI with Secrets
        on: [push]
        jobs:
            build:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                - name: Setup Node.js
                    uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                        with:
                        node-version: 18
                - run: npm install
                - name: Run app with secret
                    env:
                        DATABASE_PASSWORD: ${{ secrets.DB_PASSWORD }}
                    run: |
                        echo "Connecting to DB with secret..."
                        node scripts/connect-db.js
    - Explanation:
        - The secret DB_PASSWORD is stored securely in GitHub and accessed only at runtime, never exposed in the codebase.
        - This keeps sensitive information safe from leaks or accidental commits.

3. Dependency Scanning:
    - Definition: Node.js projects use many packages. Some may have known vulnerabilities. CI/CD should automatically scan dependencies and warn or block builds.
    - Tools:
        npm audit – built-in Node.js dependency scanning
        Snyk – detects vulnerabilities and suggests fixes
        OWASP Dependency-Check – security scanning for many languages
    - Node.js example with GitHub Actions + npm audit:
        jobs:
            security-check:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                - uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                    with:
                    node-version: 18
                - run: npm install
                - name: Run npm audit
                    run: npm audit --audit-level=high
    - Explanation:
        - npm audit checks all dependencies for high-severity vulnerabilities.
        - You can fail the pipeline if any critical issues exist, preventing unsafe code from being merged.
    - Snyk example (optional for more advanced scanning):
        - name: Run Snyk scan
            uses: snyk/actions/node@master
            with:
                args: test
            env:
                SNYK_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.SNYK_TOKEN }}

4. Pipeline Policies:
    - Definition: Enforce rules in your CI/CD pipeline to prevent risky code from being deployed.
    - Examples of policies:
        Block merge if tests fail
        Block merge if vulnerabilities are detected
        Require code reviews or approval by security team
    - GitHub example: Branch protection rules
        Go to your GitHub repo → Settings → Branches → Branch protection rules
        Enable:
            Require status checks (like build, test, security-scan) to pass before merging
            Require pull request reviews
            Enforce linear history
    - Explanation:
        - If npm test or npm audit fails, the pipeline status is red, and GitHub will block merging into main until fixed.
        - This ensures only secure, tested code gets deployed.